<DOC><DOCNO> AP881003-0346 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-88 1836EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u f AM-WorkStation     10-03 0228</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Work Station,0237</SECOND><HEAD>Silicon Graphics Announces Cheaper Work Station</HEAD><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Silicon Graphics Inc. is scheduled to announceon Tuesday a computer work station with three-dimensional graphicsthat is priced at less than $16,000, a direct challenge to neighborSun Microsystems Inc.   Sun Microsystems' least expensive three-dimensional graphicsworkstation starts at slightly more than $30,000.   Work stations are fast versions of personal computers and areused mainly by scientists, engineers and lately business andfinance professionals.   Silicon Graphics, which like Sun is based in Mountain View,Calif., already has a line of work stations priced from $45,000 to$90,000. That line has captured about 25 percent of the $600million high-end work station market, according to the currentissue of Business Week.   The Personal Iris is the cheapest member of a new family of workstations, including six members of the Iris Power family that startat $54,900.   ``This is the most significant product announcement in thehistory of the company,'' James H. Clark, the chairman and founder,said in a news release.   In another recent boost, Silicon Graphics last month licensedits three-dimensional graphics technology to International BusinessMachines Corp.   IBM and Digital Equipment Corp. are preparing to make majormoves into the work station market, which has been dominated by thelikes of Sun, Silicon Graphics and Apollo Computer Inc. ofChelmsford, Mass.</TEXT></DOC>